text:
In chapter 4 of eleqoent javascript, we were assigned to find the sum of a range by first writing a range function that created an array of numbers based on a start and ending number provided by the user. Next we were instructed to write a sum function that took the array from our range function and provided the sum of all its numbers.
The exact wording was as follows:
Write a range function that takes two arguments, start and end, and returns an array containing all the numbers 
from start up to (and including) end.

Next, write a sum function that takes an array of numbers and returns the sum of these numbers. Run the example
program and see whether it does indeed return 55.
For my solution to the range function part I used basic iteration to start with the beginning number and keep going until it reached the end number provided. This was done by pushing the elements that were iterated into a blank array I defined at the start after they were looked at to see if they were the ending number.
The code looked like this:
function range(start, end) {
    const result = [];
    for (let i = start; i &lt;= end; i++) {
      result.push(i);
    }
    return result;
  }
Next, looking at the sum function I used the reduce method to simplify the array from the range function into one singular value that can be called the sum of the range.
The code looked like this:
function sum(numbers) {
    return numbers.reduce((total, number) =&gt; total + number, 0);
  }
At the time I had used AI assistance to help me understand the reduce method as a solution to my problem, mainly the total and number parts. total being the number provided by reducing the range function to one value, and number being the current element being proccessed.

In chapter 2 of eleoquent javascript we were asked to make a chessboard that consisted of # and empty space in an alternating sequence. The criteria was that you had to make an 8 x 8 grid consisting of these alternating symbols to construct the chessboard using newlines to go to the next set. Afterwards we were challenged to modify the code in order to work with any parameters for the height and width of the chessboard, even if it was uneven. And this is were this seemingly easy problem at first became a lot harder. The main problem being that it wasn’t too hard to make a chessboard that followed an even number as the paramater, but odd numbers caused some issues.
The exact wording of the problem was as follows:
Write a program that creates a string that represents an 8×8 grid, using newline characters to separate lines. At each position of the grid there is either a space or a "#" character. The characters should form a chessboard.

Passing this string to console.log should show something like this:

 # # # #
# # # # 
 # # # #
# # # # 
 # # # #
# # # # 
 # # # #
# # # #

When you have a program that generates this pattern, define a binding size = 8 and change the program so that it
works for any size, outputting a grid of the given width and height.
To accomplish the desired result I had to first define a height and width parameter that the user provides for the program. Then using nested for loops I had it check the rows and collumns to see where the chessboard was currently at with the main kicker being the if statement that determined whether the next element in the chessboard was to be a # or empty space. Finally the loop created a newline after it had reached the desired width for the line, and continued until it reached the desired height.
My code was as follows:
const height = 8;
const width = 8;
let chessboard = '';

for (let row = 0; row &lt; height; row++) {
  for (let col = 0; col &lt; width; col++) {
    if ((row + col) % 2 === 0) {
      chessboard += ' ';
    } else {
      chessboard += '#';
    }
  }
  chessboard += '\n';
}

console.log(chessboard);
This solution took a lot of AI assistance when it came to trying to make my program run with odd and even parameters. Mainly the newline part of the code was where I got stuck on, but after some coaching I managed to get a solution that fit my purposes.

Creating Password Length
Html
&lt;div id="password-generator-container"&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;label for="passwordLength"&gt;Password Length:&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;input type="number" id="passwordLength" min="2" max="50" value="8"&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
the html code uses the built in label and input methods. I use the input method to allow the user to input a number into the provided box. I have it set to have a default value of 8 when you first load the page, with a minimum password size of 2 and a maximum size of 50. As for the label method, all it does is add the words password length above the input box
Javascript
let password = '';

function generatePassword() {
const length = document.getElementById('passwordLength').value;
}
The javascript code at this point is not too special and is only beginning to make the function by setting up some of the variables and assigning them values

Adding in the checkboxes for password generation
Next up I added in the checkboxes for including special characters, uppercase letters, and numbers by including the following code:
Html
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;div id="password-generator-container"&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;input type="checkbox" id="includeUppercase" checked&gt;
            &lt;label for="includeUppercase"&gt;Include Uppercase&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;input type="checkbox" id="includeNumbers" checked&gt;
            &lt;label for="includeNumbers"&gt;Include Numbers&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;input type="checkbox" id="includeSpecialChars" checked&gt;
            &lt;label for="includeSpecialChars"&gt;Include Special Characters&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
The following html code adds in the check boxes using the aforementioned input and label methods, but this time setting the type in input to checkbox.
Javascript
function generatePassword() {
    const includeUppercase = document.getElementById('includeUppercase').checked;
    const includeNumbers = document.getElementById('includeNumbers').checked;
    const includeSpecialChars = document.getElementById('includeSpecialChars').checked;

    const lowercaseChars = 'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz';
    const uppercaseChars = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ';
    const numberChars = '0123456789';
    const specialChars = '!#$?%&';

    let chars = lowercaseChars;

    if (includeUppercase) {
        chars += uppercaseChars;
    }

    if (includeNumbers) {
        chars += numberChars;
    }

    if (includeSpecialChars) {
        chars += specialChars;
    }
}
with these parts added to the function, you start to see that I have defined a starting set of letters available to be used in password generation named chars, whose starting value is set to the lowercase letter alphabet. When the user checks one of the boxes to include a specific feature, then it adds the provided array to the existing chars variable.

Password Generation
Now that most of the function for creating the array that the password will generate from, it is time to actually include the code to randomly generate from it.
Html
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;div id="password-generator-container"&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;button onclick="generatePassword()"&gt;Generate Password&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;label for="generatedPassword"&gt;Generated Password:&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;input type="text" id="generatedPassword" readonly&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
Javascript
function generatePassword() {
    password = ''; 
    for (let i = 0; i &lt; length; i++) {
        const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * chars.length);
        password += chars.charAt(randomIndex);
    }

    document.getElementById('generatedPassword').value = password;
}
This part of the code is the bread and butter of the function as it is what randomly selects characters from the array to add to the password. Starting from nothing, the code continues to loop until it reaches the specified length from the password length the user set in the beginning. By using math.floor I ensure that the code picks a whole number, which is needed to be able to select the corresponding character out of the array, and math.random is used to generate that random number.

Copying to the clipboard
This part of the program was something I really wanted to add, but had no clue how to go about doing it. So after consulting chatGPT for a while I finally managed to get the functionality into my code, where I then styled it as desired.
The chat logs were as follows
Me:
how do i add a copy to clipboard option for my generated password

chatGPT:
You can add a "Copy to Clipboard" functionality to your generated password by modifying the JavaScript code. Here's an updated version of the script that includes a function for copying the generated password to the clipboard:
function generatePassword() {
    const length = document.getElementById('passwordLength').value;
    const includeUppercase = document.getElementById('includeUppercase').checked;
    const includeNumbers = document.getElementById('includeNumbers').checked;
    const includeSpecialChars = document.getElementById('includeSpecialChars').checked;

    const lowercaseChars = 'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz';
    const uppercaseChars = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ';
    const numberChars = '0123456789';
    const specialChars = '!@#$%^&*()_+[]{}|;:,.&lt;&gt;?';

    let chars = lowercaseChars;

    if (includeUppercase) {
        chars += uppercaseChars;
    }

    if (includeNumbers) {
        chars += numberChars;
    }

    if (includeSpecialChars) {
        chars += specialChars;
    }

    let password = '';
    for (let i = 0; i &lt; length; i++) {
        const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * chars.length);
        password += chars.charAt(randomIndex);
    }

    const generatedPasswordInput = document.getElementById('generatedPassword');
    generatedPasswordInput.value = password;

    // Add copy to clipboard functionality
    const copyButton = document.getElementById('copyButton');
    copyButton.addEventListener('click', () =&gt; {
        generatedPasswordInput.select();
        document.execCommand('copy');
        alert('Password copied to clipboard!');
    });
}
In your HTML, add a button for copying the password:
&lt;!-- ... existing HTML code ... --&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
    &lt;button id="copyButton"&gt;Copy to Clipboard&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;!-- ... existing HTML code ... --&gt;
chatGPT:
This code selects the content of the generated password input field when the "Copy to Clipboard" button is clicked and executes the document.execCommand('copy') command to copy the selected text to the clipboard. It also displays an alert to notify the user that the password has been copied.
It was at this point that I realized what the code was doing, but vs code did not like the document.execCommand(‘copy’) line. when I told chatGPT this it provided me with the following more up to date version of the code which did work
const copyButton = document.querySelector('#copyButton');

copyButton.addEventListener('click', () =&gt; {
    navigator.clipboard.writeText(password)
        .then(() =&gt; {
            alert('Password copied to clipboard!');
        })
        .catch(err =&gt; {
            console.error('Unable to copy to clipboard', err);
        });
});

Styling
For those interested in the styling of the password generator, the code is as follows:
&lt;style&gt;
    #password-generator-container {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            text-align: center;
            margin: 50px;
            background-color: #ADD8E6;
        }

        #password-generator-container h1 {
            color: #333;
        }

        #password-generator-container div {
            margin-bottom: 15px;
        }

        #password-generator-container label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 5px;
            font-size: 1.2em;
        }

        #password-generator-container input {
            padding: 8px;
            font-size: 1em;
        }

        #password-generator-container button {
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 1em;
            cursor: pointer;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }

        #password-generator-container button:hover {
            background-color: #45a049;
        }

        #password-generator-container #password {
            font-size: 1.5em;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }

        #password-generator-container #generatedPassword {
            white-space: nowrap;
            overflow-x: scroll; 
            max-width: 100%;
        }

        #password-generator-container #copyButton {
            cursor: pointer;
            background-color: #008CBA;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            padding: 8px;
        }

        #password-generator-container #copyButton:hover {
            background-color: #0077A2;
        }
&lt;/style&gt;
I mostly just messed around with the values for most of the styling until it ended up in the spots that I wanted, and ultimately I am happy with how it turned out
